ers, Niehuus explores the renegotiation of relationships with land as a form of public healing, the affective experience of living in insecurity, the hospital as a site for the socialization of pain, the possibility of necropolitical healing, and the uses of prophesy to create collective futures. By considering the radical nature of cohabitating with violence, Niehuus demonstrates that Congolese practices of healing imagine and articulate alternative ways of living in a global regime of antiblackness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrofuturism. 0aFeminism. 0aHealingzCongo (Democratic Republic)xPsychological aspects. 0aPolitical violencezCongo (Democratic Republic). 0aRacism against Black people. 0aViolencexHealth aspectszCongo (Democratic Republic). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027881?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027881/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles